{
  "query": "In a zoo environment, what are the documented effects of altering the timing and predictability of feeding schedules for captive primates and carnivores?",
  "relevant_summary": "Research on altering feeding schedules in zoo environments shows several documented effects. For primates, one replicated, controlled study found that when chimpanzees were fed on unpredictable schedules, their inactivity decreased (Action 1338). For carnivores, multiple studies demonstrate benefits of unpredictable feeding schedules: three replicated studies found that random temporal feeding reduced stereotypic pacing behaviors in tigers and cheetahs (Action 1904), and two studies found increased behavioral diversity in red foxes and alertness in black-footed cats with unpredictable schedules (Action 1904). However, effects vary by species, as one study found that unpredictable feeding increased territorial behavior in coyotes but did not affect traveling or foraging (Action 1904). Regarding feeding frequency, one study found that large felids fed once every three days paced more frequently on non-feeding days (Action 1906). Presenting feeds during different crowd levels also showed effects, with one study finding that chimpanzees increased foraging and object use when smaller crowds were present (Action 1324).",
