{
  "query": "What dietary management strategies are available for captive primates to reduce aggression and abnormal behaviours?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several dietary management strategies have been shown to reduce aggression and abnormal behaviors in captive primates. Formulating diets to reflect the nutritional composition of wild foods, including removal of domestic fruits, resulted in lower aggression and self-directed behavior in lemurs (Action 1329). Scattering food throughout the enclosure increased feeding and exploratory behaviors in rhesus macaques, reduced abnormal behaviors in chimpanzees, and decreased aggression in lemurs, while also increasing foraging behavior and activity levels in gorillas (Action 1315). Providing cut branches (browse) allowed captive gorillas to use the same processing skills as wild gorillas when foraging with stinging nettles (Action 1332). Changing the number of feeds per day showed mixed results, with increased feeding time in chimpanzees but also increased hair eating in baboons (Action 1337).",
